ir Philip Sidney's works in the 1590s, Ben Jonson's folio Workes (1616), and the posthumous editions of the poems of Donne and of Herbert (both 1633). Marotti also considers how certain material features of the book determined the reception of poetry, and he explores how poets attempted to establish their authority in print in relation to publishers, patrons, and readers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish poetryyEarly modern, 1500-1700xCriticism, Textual. 0aEnglish poetryyEarly modern, 1500-1700xManuscripts. 0aLiterature publishingzEnglandxHistory. 0aManuscripts, RenaissancezEnglandxHistory. 0aPrintingzEnglandxHistoryy16th century. 0aPrintingzEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aRenaissancezEngland. 0aTransmission of texts. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172850140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501728501423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501728501/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles